162. margine gramineo patulos succinctus hiatus, ‘its wide basin surrounded with a grassy marge.' Succinctus is used here in a middle sense, cf. 42, 43 n., but differs from erectus, l. 43, in that it takes an accusative, hiatus. It is a very common construction in the Latin poets, and was used by them on the analogy of the double use of the participle in Greek, eg. κεκρεμασμένος τοὺς πόδας and κεκρεμασμείὀς τὴν ἀσπίδα, ‘hung up by the feet' and ‘having hung up one's shield ’. 111 501116 instances the participle is practi- cally active in meaning, cf. V. Aen. xi. 507 ‘oculos in virgine fixus ², in others it is passive with an accusative of respect, cf. Aen. iii. 47 ‘mentem formidine pressus ', and in others, as in the present instance, there is neither special active nor reflexive meaning, cf. Met. xi. 368 ‘rubra suffusus lumina flamma’, and the accusative is merely retained with the passive form.

The spring rose in the cave, and formed a basin with a grassy margin in the floor of the cave.
